<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Normal Distribution</h1>=20


<p>Data can be "distributed" (spread out) in different ways.</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">It can be spread out<br>
more on the left</td>
			<td style=3D"width:50px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"right"><br>
Or more on the right</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
data/images/normal-distribution-skew-left.svg" alt=3D"data skewed left" hei=
ght=3D"177" width=3D"202"></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
data/images/normal-distribution-skew-right.svg" alt=3D"data skewed right" h=
eight=3D"177" width=3D"202"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">Or it can be all jumbled up</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
data/images/normal-distribution-random.svg" alt=3D"data random" height=3D"1=
77" width=3D"206"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>But in many cases the data tends to be around a central value, with no b=
ias left or right, and it gets close to a "Normal Distribution" like this:<=
/p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/norm=
al-distribution-1.svg" alt=3D"bell curve hdr" height=3D"174" width=3D"384">=
</p>=20
<p class=3D"center">The blue curve is a Normal Distribution.<br>
The yellow <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/histograms.html">hist=
ogram</a> shows some data that<br>
follows it  closely, but not perfectly (which is usual).</p>

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/bell.jpg" alt=3D"=
bell" height=3D"93" width=3D"100"></td>
			<td>It is often called a "Bell Curve"<br>
because it looks like a bell.</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>Many things closely follow a Normal Distribution:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>heights of people</li>=20
	<li>size of manufactured products</li>=20
	<li>measurement errors</li>=20
	<li>blood pressure</li>=20
	<li>test scores</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>We say the data is "normally distributed":</p>=20
<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/data/images/normal-distribution-2.svg" alt=3D"normal distributio=
n with mean median mode at center" height=3D"162" width=3D"299"></p>=20
<p>The&nbsp;<b>Normal&nbsp;Distribution</b>&nbsp;has:</p>=20
<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/mean.html">mean</a> =3D <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/median.html">median</a> =3D <a href=3D"https=
://www.mathsisfun.com/mode.html">mode</a></li>=20
	<li>symmetry about the center</li>=20
	<li>50% of values less than the mean<br>
and 50% greater than the mean</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Quincunx</h2>

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>=20

<p>You can see a normal distribution being created by random chance!</p>=20
<p>It is called the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/quincunx.htm=
l">Quincunx</a> and it is an amazing machine.</p>=20
<p>Have a play with it!</p></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/quincunx.html"><img src=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/quincunx.jpg" alt=3D"quincunx" h=
eight=3D"172" width=3D"129"></a></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20


<h2>Standard Deviations</h2>=20

<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation.html">=
Standard Deviation</a> is a measure of how spread out numbers are (read tha=
t page for details on how to calculate it).</p>=20
<p>When we <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation-ca=
lculator.html">calculate the standard deviation</a> we  find that <b>approx=
imately</b>:</p>

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/normal-distrubuti=
on-3sds.svg" alt=3D"normal distrubution 68%, 95%, 99.7%" height=3D"480" wid=
th=3D"299"></td>
			<td>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p><b>68%</b> of values are within<br>
<b>1 standard deviation</b>                    of the mean</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p><b>95%</b> of values are within<br>
<b>2 standard deviations</b> of the mean</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p><b>99,7%</b> of values are within <b><br>
3 standard deviations</b> of the mean</p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 95% of students at school are between <b>1,1m and 1,7m</b> ta=
ll.</h3>=20

	<p>Assuming this data is <b>normally distributed</b> can you calculate the=
  mean and standard deviation?</p>=20
	<p>The mean is halfway between 1,1m and 1,7m:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">Mean =3D (1,1m + 1,7m) / 2 =3D <b>1,4m</b></p>=
=20
	<p>95% is 2 standard deviations either side of the mean (a total of 4 stan=
dard deviations) so:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">1 standard deviation</span></td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">=3D (1,7m-1,1m) / 4</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">=3D 0,6m / 4</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">=3D <b>0,15m</b></span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"right">And this is the result:</span><b=
r>
<img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/normal-distribution-exb1=
.svg" alt=3D"normal distribution 95%" height=3D"142" width=3D"260"></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>It is good to know  the standard deviation, because we can say that any =
value is:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>likely</b> to be within 1 standard deviation (68 out of 100 should =
be)</li>=20
	<li><b>very likely</b> to be within 2 standard deviations (95 out of 100 s=
hould be)</li>=20
	<li><b>almost certainly</b> within 3 standard deviations (997 out of 1000 =
should be)</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Standard Scores</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>The number of <b>standard deviations from the mean</b> is also called th=
e "Standard Score", "sigma" or "z-score". Get used to those words!</p>=20
</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: In that same school one of your friends is 1,85m tall</h3>=20

	<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;">&nbsp;</p> <span style=3D"=
float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
data/images/normal-distribution-exb1.svg" alt=3D"normal distribution 95%" h=
eight=3D"142" width=3D"260"></span>=20
	<p>You can see on the bell curve that 1,85m is <b>3 standard deviations</b=
> from the mean of 1,4, so:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"larger">Your friend's height has a "z-score" of 3,0</p>=20
	<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<p>It is also possible to <b>calculate</b> how many standard deviations 1,8=
5 is from the mean</p>=20
<p><i>How far is 1,85 from the mean?</i></p>=20
<p class=3D"center">It is 1,85 - 1,4 =3D<b> 0,45m from the mean</b></p>=20
<p><i>How many standard deviations is that?</i> The standard deviation is 0=
,15m, so:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center">0,45m / 0,15m =3D <b>3 standard deviations</b></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>To convert a value to a Standard Score ("z-score"):</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>first  subtract the mean,</li>=20
	<li>then divide by the Standard Deviation</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And doing that is called "Standardizing":</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stan=
dardizing.svg" alt=3D"standardizing" style=3D"max-width:100%" height=3D"169=
" width=3D"609"></p>=20
<p>We can take any Normal Distribution and convert it to  The Standard Norm=
al Distribution.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Travel Time</h3>=20

	<p>A survey of daily travel time had these results (in minutes):</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">26, 33, 65, 28, 34, 55, 25, 44, 50, 36, 26, 37, 43, 62=
, 35, 38, 45, 32, 28, 34</p>=20
	<p>The <b>Mean is 38,8 minutes</b>, and the <b>Standard Deviation is 11,4 =
minutes</b> (you can copy and paste the values into the <a href=3D"https://=
www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation-calculator.html">Standard Deviat=
ion Calculator</a> if you want).</p>=20
	<p>Convert the values to z-scores ("standard scores").</p>=20
	<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
	<p>To convert  <b>26</b>:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"so"> first subtract the mean: 26 =E2=88=92 38,8 =3D =E2=88=
=9212,8,</div>
<div class=3D"so">then divide by the Standard Deviation: =E2=88=9212,8/11,4=
 =3D <span class=3D"hilite">=E2=88=921,12</span></div>
<p>So <b>26</b> is <b>=E2=88=921,12 Standard Deviations</b> from the Mean</=
p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>Here are the first three conversions</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">Original Value</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">Calculation</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">Standard Score<br>
(z-score)</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>26</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(26-38,8) / 11,4 =3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>=E2=88=921,12</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>33</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(33-38,8) / 11,4 =3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>=E2=88=920,51</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>65</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(65-38,8) / 11,4 =3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>+2,30</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>And here they are graphically:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stan=
dard-normal-distribution-scores.gif" alt=3D"standard normal distribution sc=
ores" height=3D"163" width=3D"263"></p>=20
<p>You can calculate the rest of the z-scores yourself!</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>The  <b>z-score formula</b> that we have been using is:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center large">z =3D <span class=3D"intbl"><em>x =E2=88=92 =CE=
=BC</em><strong>=CF=83</strong></span></p>=20
</div>=20

<ul>=20
	<li><b>z</b> is the "z-score" (Standard Score)</li>=20
	<li><b>x</b> is the value to be standardized</li>=20
	<li><b>=CE=BC</b> ('mu") is the mean</li>=20
	<li><b>=CF=83</b> ("sigma") is the standard deviation</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And this is how to use it:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Travel Time (continued)</h3>=20

	<p>Here are the first three conversions using the "z-score formula":</p>=
=20
	<p class=3D"center large">z =3D <span class=3D"intbl"><em>x =E2=88=92 =CE=
=BC</em><strong>=CF=83</strong></span></p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>=CE=BC =3D 38,8</li>=20
		<li>=CF=83 =3D 11,4</li>=20
	</ul>

	<table class=3D"center" border=3D"1">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"center">x</th>
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"center"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>x =E2=88=92=
 =CE=BC</em><strong>=CF=83</strong></span></th>
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"center">z<br>
(z-score)</th>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">26</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>26 =E2=88=92 =
38,8</em><strong>11,4</strong></span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D =E2=88=921,12</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">33</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>33 =E2=88=92 =
38,8</em><strong>11,4</strong></span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D =E2=88=920,51</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">65</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>65 =E2=88=92 =
38,8</em><strong>11,4</strong></span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D +2,30</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:right;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">...</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
	<p>The exact calculations we did before, just following the formula.</p>=
=20
</div>=20


<h2>Why Standardize ... ?</h2>=20

<p>It can help us make decisions about our data.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Professor Willoughby is marking a test.</h3>=20

	<p>Here are the students' results (out of 60 points):</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">20, 15, 26, 32, 18, 28, 35, 14, 26, 22, 17</p>=20
	<p>Most students didn't even get 30 out of 60, and<b> most will fail</b>.<=
/p>=20
	<p>The test must have been really hard,  so the Prof  decides to Standardi=
ze  all the scores and only fail people more than 1 standard deviation belo=
w the mean.</p>=20
	<p>The <b>Mean is 23</b>, and the <b>Standard Deviation is 6,6</b>, and th=
ese are the Standard Scores:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">-0,45,  <span class=3D"hilite">-1,21</span>,  0,45,  1=
,36,  -0,76,  0,76,  1,82,  <span class=3D"hilite">-1,36</span>,  0,45,  -0=
,15,  -0,91</p>=20
	<p>Now only 2 students will <span class=3D"hilite">fail</span> (the ones l=
ower than =E2=88=921 standard deviation)</p>=20
	<p>Much fairer!</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>It also makes life easier because we only need  one table (the <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-normal-distribution-table.html=
">Standard Normal Distribution Table</a>), rather than doing calculations i=
ndividually for each value of mean and standard deviation.</p>=20


<h2>In More Detail</h2>=20

<p>Here is the Standard Normal Distribution with percentages for every <b>h=
alf of a standard deviation</b>, and cumulative percentages:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/norm=
al-distrubution-large.svg" alt=3D"normal distrubution large bell curve" sty=
le=3D"max-width:100%" height=3D"329" width=3D"650"></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: Your score in a recent test was <b>0,5 standard deviations</b>=
 above the average, how many people scored<b> lower</b> than you did?</p>=
=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>Between 0 and 0,5  is <b>19,1%</b></li>=20
		<li>Less than 0 is <b>50%</b> (left half of the curve)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So the total less than you is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">50% + 19,1% =3D 69,1%</p>=20
	<p>In theory <b>69,1% scored less</b> than you did (but with real data the=
 percentage may be different)</p>=20
</div>=20

<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/measure/images/measuring-1kg-2.jpg" alt=3D"measuring 1kg " heigh=
t=3D"240" width=3D"200"></p>=20


<h2>A Practical Example: Your company packages sugar in 1 kg bags.</h2>=20

<p>When you weigh a sample of   bags you get these results:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>1007g, 1032g, 1002g, 983g, 1004g, ... (a hundred measurements)</li>=20
	<li>Mean =3D 1010g</li>=20
	<li>Standard Deviation =3D 20g</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p><b>Some values are less than 1000g ... can you fix that?</b></p>=20
<p>The normal distribution of your measurements looks like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/norm=
al-distribution-ex1.gif" alt=3D"normal distribution ex1" height=3D"150" wid=
th=3D"258"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">31% of the bags are less than 1000g,<br>
which is cheating the customer!</p>=20
<p>It is a random thing, so we can't  <b>stop</b> bags having less than 100=
0g, but we can try to <b>reduce it</b> a lot.</p>=20
<p>Let's adjust the machine so that 1000g is ...</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">... at =E2=88=923 standard deviations:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">From the big bell curve above we  see  that only <b=
>0,1%</b> are less. But maybe that is too small.</div>
<p class=3D"center larger">... at =E2=88=922,5 standard deviations:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">Below 3 is 0,1% and between 3 and 2,5 standard devi=
ations  is 0,5%, together that is 0,1% + 0,5% =3D <b>0,6%</b> (a good choic=
e I think)</div>
<p>So let us adjust the machine to have <b>1000g at =E2=88=922,5 standard d=
eviations</b> from the mean.</p>=20
<p>Now, we can adjust it to:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>increase the amount of sugar in each bag (which  changes the mean), or=
</li>=20
	<li>make it more accurate (which  reduces the standard deviation)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Let us try both.</p>=20

<h4>Adjust the mean amount in each bag</h4>=20

<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.mat=
hsisfun.com/data/images/normal-distribution-ex2.gif" alt=3D"normal distribu=
tion ex2" height=3D"145" width=3D"330"></p>=20
<p>The standard deviation is 20g, and we need 2,5 of them:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">2,5 =C3=97 20g =3D 50g</p>=20
<p>So the machine should average <b>1050g</b>, like this:</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20

<h4>Adjust the accuracy of the machine</h4>=20

<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.mat=
hsisfun.com/data/images/normal-distribution-ex3.gif" alt=3D"normal distribu=
tion ex3" height=3D"150" width=3D"258"></p>=20
<p>Or we can keep the same mean (of 1010g), but then we  need 2,5 standard =
deviations  to be equal to 10g:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">10g / 2,5 =3D 4g</p>=20
<p>So the standard deviation should be <b>4g</b>, like this:</p>=20
<p>(We hope the machine is that accurate!)</p>=20
<p>Or perhaps we could have some combination of better accuracy and slightl=
y larger average size, I will leave that up to you!</p>=20


<h2>More Accurate Values ...</h2>=20

<p>Use the  <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-normal-dist=
ribution-table.html">Standard Normal Distribution Table</a> when you want m=
ore accurate values.</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
